The article is a transcript of remarks made by Vice President Mike Pence at the United States Military Academy at West Point. Pence expressed gratitude to the cadets for their service and reiterated President Donald Trump's commitment to standing with and supporting the military. He also spoke about the legacy of Henry O. Flipper, the first African American graduate of West Point, and recognized the accomplishments of cadet Lars Lofgren, who was paralyzed but continued to serve and excel. Pence emphasized the importance of the military in protecting the country from threats such as radical Islamic terrorism and assured the cadets that the administration would provide the resources and training needed to accomplish their mission. He concluded by expressing confidence in America's future and the potential of the cadets.